You can try to create an utility service for building the params part of your URL. The utility method will get input from a List&lt;String&gt; and build a String through StringBuffer. The result will be a String written as when you write param manually. Now you can use the Pre-Parser syntax built in thymeleaf to call the utility and build your final url.
Here the example:

Utility Service

    @Service(&quot;thymeleafUtilsService&quot;)
    public class ThymeleafUtilsService
    {
    
        public String buildMultiParamPartUrl(List&lt;String&gt; paramNames)
        {
            StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer(0);
    
            for ( String paramName : paramNames )
            {
                if ( sb.length() &gt;= 0 )
                {
                    sb.append(&quot;,&quot;);
                }
                sb.append(paramName).append(&quot;=${&quot;).append(paramName).append(&quot;}&quot;);
            }
    
            return sb.toString();
        }
    
    }

